Central Committee of Jews in Poland, 1946–1950 -- tChapter 8 Risks and Results of Citizens’ Commitments: The Kačerovski Case in Riga, 1958–1963 -- tChapter 9 Mediators behind the Scenes: The World Jewish Congress and the International Auschwitz Committee during the Preparations for the First Auschwitz Trial in Frankfurt -- tB. Individual and Collective Advocacy -- tChapter 10 Accusing Hans Globke, 1960–1963 Agency and the Iron Curtain -- tChapter 11 The Fils et Filles des Déportés Juifs de France and the Lischka Trial in Cologne, 1971–1980 -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe thirst for post-World War II justice transcended the Cold War and mobilized diverse social groups. This is a story of their multilayered and at times conflictual interactions.In this edited collection, sixteen historians develop a new approach to the trials against persons accused of war crimes and mass murder in Europe during the ascendancy of Nazism and the Second World War (1933-1945). Focusing on the social aspects of the demand for justice and making use of previously underexploited local and international sources, contributors put to the test the notion of "show trials" and explore a range of judicial and political cultures from Germany to the Soviet Union. Essays uncover the expectations around accountability and forms of mobilization on the part of a range of citizens involved in the trials: survivors, witnesses, perpetrators, Nazi hunters, and civic activists. In addition to the perspective of these citizens, contributors invoke the expertise of reporters, filmmakers, historians, investigators, and prosecutors who shaped public representations of justice. These shaping efforts, the authors show, often supported the desire of political authorities to benefit from the publicity of the trials and to contain the spontaneous dissemination of information. The book's close examination of interactions between citizens and authorities thus demonstrates the extent and limits of what might be called a "coproduction" of justice, in the process shedding light on the interdependence between historical knowledge and legal prosecution of mass crimes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWar crime trialsxHistoryy20th centuryzEurope, Eastern. 0aWar crime trialsxHistoryy20th centuryzGermany. 0aWar crime trialszEurope, Central. 0aWar crime trialszEurope, Eastern. 0aWar crimeszEurope, Central. 0aWar crimeszEurope, Eastern. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocities. 4aEast European Studies. 4aGerman History. 4aJewish Studies. 4aModern History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Genocide & War Crimes.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aNazi war crimes.  aNazism.  aaccountability.  aauthorities.  acitizens.  acoproduction of justice.  ahistorical knowledge.  ajustice demand.  alegal prosecution.  amass murder.  apolitical cultures.  apost-World War II justice.  asocial interactions.  atrials.  awar crimes.1 aBarbat, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourhis, Eric Le, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeitzer, Enrico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlarzyk, Birte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlein, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLachwitz, Götz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandau, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Bourhis, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindeperg, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerson, Katarzyna, econtributor.4ctb4h